treasury_media.title: May 29th - Meeting with Dutch Government Officials
treasury_media.description: On May 29th from 13:00 to 14:00, join us as we peacefully gather together in The Hague to deliver a petition to Parliament. It has been already signed by over 28,000 individuals. Comprised of representatives from the United Expats of the Netherlands (UENL) along with members of diverse political, corporate, and academic entities, the petition requests that the Dutch government honors its commitment to highly skilled expats who are currently recipients of the 30% tax ruling.

profile_positions.description:
Engelbert Felberthann is the Co-Founder of “United Expats of The Netherlands”. With over 35,000 followers currently working as highly skilled expats in the Netherlands, United Expats formed in April 2018 in response to a proposal of the Ministry of Finance to dishonor an existing commitment between the Dutch government and highly skilled expats currently living in the Netherlands.

Our petition against the proposed 30% Tax Ruling has attracted over 35,000 international professionals currently working as expats in the Netherlands. It is recognized as one of the largest, most comprehensive and best organized grassroots movements in the history of the Netherlands.
 
As the Chair of Corporate Outreach, Engelbert is leading a national grassroots movements and corporate initiative to encourage the Dutch business community (e.g. corporations, academic institutions, non-profit sectors) to support the United Expats as they work to encourage the Dutch government to stand by the promise it made with thousands of expats in the Netherlands - #AfspraakisAfspraak https://www.adealisadeal.nl/our-stories/

For more information, please check out our website @ www.adealisadeal.nl
profile_positions.title: Co-Founder and Chair of Corporate Outreach - #AfspraakisAfspraak

profile_positions.description:
Stichting Mama Watoto (Swahili = Mother of children) is an independent, international non-profit organization that was founded in 2007 by a group of African women living in the Netherlands. The regional focus lies in rural areas in the Teso region in the North-East of Uganda.

Our mission is to protect, support, and empower the lives of abandoned street children, displaced teenagers and young child mothers through counseling, housing, and a variety of educational programs. Our goal is to help these young and highly traumatized individuals to effect a positive and sustainable change for themselves and the communities they live in. 

Many of these girls and boys are HIV infected or have been brutally abused or raped during the local rebel war started by Joseph Kony, who was indicted for crimes against humanity in 2005. Unfortunately these young people are mostly forgotten and don’t receive any further attention from their government or any charity organization.

We believe that everybody deserves the opportunity to live a safe, productive, and fulfilled life. 
Together, we can make it happen, so why don’t we?  For more information, including your donations please visit our website www.mamawatoto.org

We are currently looking for dedicated and passionate volunteers in the areas of fundraising, back-end and front-end development, project management, and PR support. Please don’t hesitate to contact me at engelbert@mamawatoto.org if you have any further questions.
